Decent, inexpensive burgers from an exhaustive, noisy menu. Tons of options for a meal, including an insanely long alcoholic drinks menu (divided by drink size; Action Burger is your go-to spot for 32-ounce beverages). Service is spotty at best, as the staff is more interested in playing the (free) video games the spot is known for. On an afternoon with two other people in the restaurant, a burger and fries took 25 minutes to come up from a mysterious door behind the counter. While the pretzel bun was not exactly fresh, the burger was fine if underseasoned and the fries cooked perfectly.  But those games! There are two emulator consoles in front, from which one can choose any of hundreds of classic arcade games to play. There are also home videogame consoles set up, with many, many rules about who can play and for how long. Basically the shop isn't interested in folks buying a soda and playing free games all evening (I can't say I blame them).  In theory credit cards are accepted, but a tattered sign at the register notes they're cash-only and probably have been for a long time.

This is primarily a bar and restaurant, coupled with a pretty substantive gaming center in the front. The space is not very big, but we had a great experience and felt it was a great value.  Came here on a weeknight for a Halo LAN party and "Mr Carter" hooked us up. We connected 3 Xboxes (combination of two originals and one 360) and played the original Halo 1 with 12 people from around 7pm to 11pm. Time flew by, we yelled and taunted each other, had a great time, and it only cost us about $100 for the whole night, or about $10 per person.  Let me qualify this review by saying that we did not eat any of the food; the manager let us bring in our own food and gave us tables upon which to eat. The drinks were pretty standard, beers and some basic well drinks, but I saw Mr Carter making milkshakes every night.  Sure, there were a few kinks with the system link, and I think they could do better in the drink department, but overall a great place.

This review is  regarding my visit in mid April. My girlfriend took me here. Where has this place been my entire life?!  Free arcade games and classic home consoles! We spent most of our time on the two arcade machines in the front. I was so thrilled that both machines have just about all the Street Fighter II versions possible. What made it more special was that they had World Heroes on one of them, a rare find since it wasn't as popular back then! Between the two machines, they had every possible classic game. The joysticks and buttons all work perfectly.  Now for the food I had. The burger was great! The wings were fantastic! The chocolate mint milkshake was amazing!  I await my next return to this palace. This place is certainly one of a kind.

Action Burger is a really fun place to go when you're in the mood for a spiced-up burger! The inside is great - filled with comic books, action figures, arcade cabinets, and more. Looking at the menu, it's all super villain/hero themed with a bunch of choices and fun names based on characters (but you don't need to know the characters to think they sound delicious)!  I went for the namesake on my first visit - the action burger - and got it topped with just lettuce and tomato; keeping it simple to taste the burger! The meat was pretty good, and had a bunch (10+) of spices on it. At first, I was apprehensive about the spices, but they really grew on me. It was a different twist on a burger that I haven't experienced yet. I'm definitely looking back to testing the other choices at this spot in the future. I think the super action burger had 20+ spices on it! Does more spices mean more flavor? I'll have to come back and find out!
Great burgers, made to order, and a cool vibe.  They also have a plethora of 80s comic books to peruse and free video games on their MAME cabinet while you wait.
